---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Do you use AI tools or subcontractors?",
    a: "No. Every job is handled personally by Lynden Howells – no AI tools, no subcontractors, no exceptions. You get 45 years of trained human judgement on your document, not an algorithm."
  },
  {
    q: "What file formats do you accept?",
    a: "Microsoft Word documents and PDFs are preferred. If you're working in another format, get in touch and we can discuss options."
  },
  {
    q: "Where are you based, and do you work with clients outside Tasmania?",
    a: "Lynden is based in Hobart, Tasmania, but works with clients across eastern Australia – including Victoria, New South Wales, and Queensland – as well as internationally. Past clients include organisations in the USA and Japan. All work is handled remotely via email, so location is no barrier."
  },
  {
    q: "Is there a minimum job size?",
    a: "No. Whether it's a one-page letter or a 200-page annual report, every job gets the same careful attention."
  },
  {
    q: "How long does proofreading take?",
    a: "A typical 20-page A4 document is returned within 2–3 business days. Rush turnaround is available on request – an urgent rate is agreed upfront before work begins."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between proofreading and copyediting?",
    a: "Proofreading focuses on catching errors – spelling, grammar, punctuation, consistency, and word usage. Copyediting goes a step further, also improving clarity, flow, and phrasing. Lynden offers both: straightforward proofreading for documents that just need a final check, and editorial suggestions for those that could benefit from more substantial improvement."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does it cost?",
    a: "Rates are hourly and vary with the complexity of the document. A simple newsletter and a highly technical scientific journal require different levels of expertise, and are priced accordingly. To get a quote, send a sample of your document and your deadline – Lynden will come back to you promptly."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I get in touch?",
    a: "Use the contact form or send an email to get started. Once a job is underway, Lynden is happy to speak by phone if needed – or you can leave your number and he'll call you back."
  },
];
---

<Layout
  title="Services"
  description="Professional proofreading, editorial services, and tender document review by Lynden Howells – 45+ years of full-time experience. All work done personally, no AI tools. Based in Hobart, Tasmania, serving clients across Australia and internationally."
>
  <!-- FAQPage structured data for Google rich results -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": faqs.map(({ q, a }) => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": q,
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": a
      }
    }))
  })} />

  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Services</h1>
      <p class="page-header__sub">Proofreading, editorial services, and tender document review</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">

      <h2 id="proofreading">Proofreading</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        Spellcheckers and grammar tools are useful – but they are not proofreaders. They
        won't catch a word that's spelled correctly but used in the wrong context. They won't
        flag that your document was drafted with American English settings when your audience
        expects Australian spelling. And they certainly won't notice when a perfectly spelled
        word changes the meaning of a sentence entirely.
      </p>
      <p>
        What I bring is a trained human eye that has been doing this – full-time, professionally –
        for over 45 years. Every document I review gets the same thorough treatment:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Spelling, including Australian vs American English consistency</li>
        <li>Grammar and punctuation</li>
        <li>Word usage and contextual accuracy</li>
        <li>Consistency of style, formatting, and terminology</li>
        <li>Typographical errors and layout anomalies</li>
        <li>Numbering, headings, and cross-references</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="editorial">Editorial Services</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        Sometimes a document is error-free but still doesn't read as well as it could.
        Beyond catching mistakes, I offer suggestions for clearer, sharper phrasing.
      </p>
      <p>
        A classic example of why this matters: a classified ad once read,
        <em>"Piano wanted for a lady with ivory legs."</em> Technically correct in spelling –
        but clearly not what the writer intended.
      </p>
      <p>
        Editorial suggestions are always presented as options, never impositions. You retain
        full control over your document. My role is to give you the information you need to
        make it the best it can be.
      </p>

      <h2 id="tenders">Tender Documents</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        Quotes and tenders are rejected on technicalities every day – a confusing layout,
        a contradictory clause, an unaddressed requirement, a grammatical error. Any of these
        can undermine a submission that is otherwise technically strong.
      </p>
      <p>
        I've been thoroughly trained in spotting the kinds of errors, omissions, and anomalies
        that evaluators notice. I don't need to be a subject matter expert in your field to do
        this effectively – in fact, fresh eyes often catch what familiarity blinds you to.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Confusing or inconsistent layout and structure</li>
        <li>Contradictions between sections</li>
        <li>Requirements from the brief that haven't been addressed</li>
        <li>Ambiguous phrasing that could be read against you</li>
        <li>Grammatical errors and spelling mistakes</li>
        <li>Formatting and numbering inconsistencies</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p style="font-family:'DM Serif Display',Georgia,serif;font-style:italic;font-size:1.05rem;margin:0;">
          "Send it to me first and your chances of success will increase. Dramatically."
        </p>
        <p style="margin-top:0.6rem;font-size:0.85rem;font-weight:500;color:var(--brown);">– Lynden Howells</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="rates">Rates &amp; Turnaround</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        My rates are hourly and vary with the complexity of the document. A straightforward
        newsletter and a highly technical annual report or prescribing information document
        are very different assignments – and I price them accordingly.
      </p>

      <div class="cards" style="margin:1.5rem 0 2rem;">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Standard turnaround</h3>
          <p>
            A typical 20-page A4 document – such as a small annual report with photos
            and graphics – is returned within <strong>2–3 business days</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Rush jobs</h3>
          <p>
            Faster turnaround is available upon request. An urgent rate is agreed
            upfront before I begin, so there are no surprises on either side.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Before accepting any job, I ask to see a sample of the work. This lets me give
        you an accurate quote and confirm I can meet your deadline. I won't quote sight
        unseen – and you wouldn't want me to.
      </p>

      <h2 id="personal">Personal service – no AI, no subcontractors</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <p>
        Every document I take on is read and reviewed by me personally. I don't use AI
        proofreading tools, and I don't pass work to subcontractors. When you engage
        Lynden's Proofreading, you get Lynden – with 45 years of professional experience
        behind every mark on the page.
      </p>

      <p class="mt-2"><a href="/contact" class="btn">Request a Quote</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <hr class="gold-rule" />
      <dl class="faq-list">
        {faqs.map(({ q, a }) => (
          <div class="faq-item">
            <dt>{q}</dt>
            <dd>{a}</dd>
          </div>
        ))}
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .faq-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0; }

  .faq-item {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding: 1.5rem 0;
  }
  .faq-item:first-child { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }

  .faq-item dt {
    font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--brown-dark);
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }

  .faq-item dd {
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
